      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional bodyweight-workout clip — ~8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Natural or soft gym-style lighting; neutral floor mat or gym floor, workout clothing with minimal distractions, warm skin tones\n* Sound: Ambient (soft floor mat contact, breath, faint room echo), no voiceover (optional breath cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Clean floor space (home, gym, or studio) with a stable elevated surface (bench, box, step, or chair) behind — enough to place feet on. Background minimal with slight blur so subject stands out.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle or side-angle (slightly low), capturing full body from head to heels — so viewer sees straight body alignment, foot elevation, hand placement, and push-up motion.\n* Subject: use reference image, Athletic adult male, wearing fitted workout clothes (t-shirt/tank + shorts/leggings), body positioned for decline push-up (feet on elevated surface, hands on floor).\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Setup — subject places feet on elevated surface (bench/box), hands slightly wider than shoulder-width on floor, body in straight plank line from head to heels, core & glutes engaged (“rigid body”).\n* 1 s–2 s: Begin descent — elbows start to bend, chest lowers toward floor; maintain a rigid torso (no sagging or excessive arch), keep head/neck neutral (eyes slightly ahead or down).\n* 2 s–4 s: Lower until chest nearly touches the floor (or close) — elbows at ~45° angle relative to torso (i.e. not flared wide), forearms vertical or slightly angled, body straight.\n* 4 s–5 s: Brief hold at bottom (~0.2–0.5 s) — feel chest/upper-pecs and shoulders under stretch/tension, core stable, glutes tight.\n* 5 s–7 s: Push up — drive through hands, extend elbows, raise chest back up, maintain straight body, prevent hips sagging or glutes rising; exhale during push.\n* 7 s–8 s: Lockout / finish pose — body straight, arms extended, chest up, shoulders stable, feet still elevated, hold briefly (~0.3–0.5 s), then optionally fade out or reset for next rep.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Upper chest (clavicular head of pectoralis major), front shoulders (anterior deltoids), triceps.\n* Secondary / Stabilizers: Core (abs, lower back), glutes & hamstrings (for whole-body stability and maintaining bodyline), also some activation in mid-chest, shoulders, and arms.\nBenefits & Purpose\n* More challenging than regular push-up: elevating feet shifts more bodyweight forward, increasing load on chest, shoulders, and arms — good for building upper-body strength without equipment.\n* Great for targeting upper-chest and front-shoulder muscles, adding variety beyond flat push-ups.\n* Also recruits core and stabilizer muscles to maintain proper body alignment — helps with overall stability, posture, and functional strength.\n\nExtra Direction & Tips\n* Keep the body in a rigid “plank” — avoid letting hips sag or butt rise.\n* Keep elbows at a ~45° angle to torso (not flared wide) to protect shoulders and maximize chest engagement.\n* Feet should rest securely on a stable elevated surface (bench, step, box). Start with lower elevation if you’re new to this variation to preserve form & avoid excessive strain.\n* Full range of motion: lower until chest nearly touches floor (or just above), then press fully up — partial reps reduce effectiveness.\n* Breathing: inhale on descent, exhale on push-up ascent — helps maintain stability and control.",
