      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength-clip, ~8 seconds\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Color & Lighting: Realistic gym tones (matte bars, neutral background, warm skin tones), slightly soft directional key light + ambient fill so subject stands out\n* Sound: Soft gym ambient (bars creak lightly, controlled breathing), no voice-over (or optional minimal breath cue)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Stable dip-bar station (parallel bars or dip bars) in a gym or clean workout area, background uncluttered and slightly blurred\n* Camera: Medium-wide side / ¾-angle — enough to show full body, bars, dipping motion clearly (elbows, torso lean, leg position)\n* Subject: use reference image, Fit adult male, wearing gym-appropriate clothing (tank or fitted tee + shorts), hands gripping bars arms locked, body hanging, ready to dip\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Starting position — arms extended, body suspended, shoulders back & down, chest up, core engaged, legs hanging or slight bend at knees, body stable\n* 1 s–2 s: Begin descent — lifter inhales, bends elbows, slowly lowers torso while maintaining control; slight forward lean if aiming more chest-focus, torso vertical if more triceps-focus.\n* 2 s–4 s: Reach bottom — lower until elbows ~90° (or until comfortable depth), chest (or sternum) slightly forward between bars, shoulders stable and not shrugging, core tight, glutes and legs still controlled.\n* 4 s–5 s: Brief pause — hold position ~0.2–0.5 s to demonstrate tension, full stretch, controlled posture.\n* 5 s–7 s: Press up — exhale, drive through hands, extend elbows, lift body back up until arms locked, shoulders stable, chest up, control maintained throughout motion.\n* 7 s–8 s: Lockout / finish pose — arms locked straight, body upright/hanging, chest up, small squeeze in chest/triceps, hold briefly (~0.5 s), then (optionally) end or flow into another rep\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: chest (pectoralis major), triceps (triceps brachii), front shoulders (anterior deltoids)\n* Secondary / Stabilizers: shoulders (deltoids), core (abs, obliques), upper-back stabilizers (scapular muscles), forearms/grip used to hold bars, plus glutes/legs for body stability.\nBenefits & Purpose\n* Efficient upper-body compound movement: engages multiple major muscle groups (chest, arms, shoulders, core) in one movement.\n* Great for building strength and muscle mass (upper body) using just bodyweight.\n* Versatile: by adjusting lean, elbow position, or adding weight you can shift emphasis (more chest vs more triceps) and scale difficulty for beginners → advanced.\nForm & Safety / Tips\n* Keep shoulders down and back (not shrugged) — helps maintain shoulder stability and reduces risk of joint strain.\n* Control the movement: no swinging or uncontrolled drops — descent and ascent should be smooth and steady.\n* Elbows: tucked or moderately out (not flared too wide) — helps protect shoulders, especially during deep dips.\n* Body lean: For more chest focus, lean slightly forward; for more triceps focus, stay more upright.\n* Progress carefully — if dips are too challenging at first, start with assisted dips (bands or bench dips) and build strength over time.",
