      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength-clip, ~8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920 × 1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Realistic gym tones — bench grey/black or dark, dumbbells metallic, warm skin tones; soft key light from above/side + mild ambient fill for clarity\n* Sound: Subtle gym ambient (weight cloth/clink, soft breath, bench creak), no voice-over (or optional gentle breath-in / breath-out cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Gym or clean home-gym setup with flat bench and pair of dumbbells — bench centered, background uncluttered or softly blurred to keep focus on lifter and weights\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle or side angle (slightly low) to capture full body — bench, dumbbells, motion path. Angle should allow clear view of dumbbells, arms, chest and torso throughout press.\n* Subject: use reference image, Athletic adult male, lying flat on bench, feet firmly planted on floor, back & shoulders in contact with bench, holding dumbbells in hands — ready to lift. Clothing: fitted gym wear (t-shirt/tank + shorts/training pants), minimal distractions\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Setup — subject lies flat on bench, dumbbells held vertically (handles upward), arms extended above chest with neutral wrist alignment, palms facing forward (or slightly turned in, per grip preference), shoulder blades retracted/pressed into bench, core engaged.\n* 1 s–2 s: Stabilize — take a deep breath, brace core, ensure feet planted, upper back and shoulders stable on bench, dumbbells steady overhead, ready to descend.\n* 2 s–4 s: Descent — lifter slowly lowers dumbbells in controlled arc, with elbows bending and lowering toward chest — arms out wide but elbows slightly bent, wrists straight. Lower until dumbbells roughly align with chest (at or just below nipple line), until stretch is felt in chest and pecs.\n* 4 s–5 s: Pause / stretch — hold bottom position ~0.2–0.5 s, feel chest muscles engaged and stretched, maintain control, avoid bouncing or dropping.\n* 5 s–7 s: Press upward — exhale, press dumbbells upward & slightly inward (optional slight arc so dumbbells meet or nearly meet at top), contracting chest (pectorals), triceps, and front shoulders; arms extend till elbows nearly locked (not hyper-locked), wrists stable.\n* 7 s–8 s: Lockout / finish pose — dumbbells overhead (or slightly above chest, meeting or near-meeting), chest up, shoulder blades stable on bench, brief squeeze, hold for ~0.5 s, then (optionally) lower or end clip with dumbbells raised. Fade to black or cut.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Chest (pectoralis major) — main driver of pressing motion.\n* Secondary: Anterior deltoids (front shoulders), triceps brachii (for elbow extension), plus stabilizers — shoulders, core, forearms (for stabilization), especially with dumbbells due to independent arm movement.\nBenefits / Why Use Dumbbells\n* More range of motion compared to barbell — dumbbells let you lower your arms wider and deeper, increasing stretch, muscle tension and chest activation.\n* Balanced development — since each arm works independently, you avoid left-right strength/muscle imbalance issues that sometimes arise with barbells.\n* Better shoulder joint comfort and safety — dumbbells allow natural arm/wrist path, often reducing shoulder stress compared to fixed-barbell pressing.\n* Also engages stabilizer muscles and core — independent dumbbells require more control, which helps with overall upper-body stability and balanced muscle activation.\nForm / Safety & Tips\n* Keep shoulder blades retracted and pressed into bench throughout — don’t let shoulders slump or roll forward. Helps protect shoulders and improves chest activation.\n* Lower dumbbells in a controlled arc, avoid dropping fast or bouncing. Drop slowly to avoid shoulder strain and maximize muscle stretch under tension.\n* At the top, press dumbbells slightly together (if comfortable) — a “converging arc” can increase chest fiber recruitment. Many lifters find that tilting dumbbells so thumbs point upward helps emphasize chest over triceps.\n* Use weights appropriate to your strength and control — heavy dumbbells require better stabilization; if too heavy, shoulders or triceps may take over instead of chest.\n* Ensure core and lower-body are stable (feet grounded, back flat on bench) — stability improves pressing power and reduces risk of injury.",
