      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic/instructional clip, ~8 seconds\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Real gym/light-studio tones — metal cable machine, neutral gym floor or mat, warm skin tone; with soft key-light + ambient fill to highlight subject and cables\n* Sound: Soft gym ambient (slight cable/weight rustle, controlled breathing), optional subtle cue, no voice-over required\nScene Setup\n* Location: Gym or home‐gym with a cable machine (dual-pulley or functional trainer), space cleared of clutter, good background blur so subject + cables stand out\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low) to capture full body — cable machine, pulley alignment, arms, torso; ensures clear view of motion and posture\n* Subject: use reference image, Fit adult male, athletic build, wearing gym attire (fitted top + shorts/leggings), standing (or seated, if using bench) in front of machine, ready to press\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Setup — position cables at or around chest/shoulder height, subject grabs both handles with overhand grip (palms facing down or neutral), feet shoulder-width, slight stagger/one foot forward if standing; back straight, core engaged\n* 1 s–2 s: Step forward slightly (if standing) so cables have tension; shoulders back, chest up, elbows bent ~90°, preparing for press.\n* 2 s–4 s: Press phase — exhale and push handles forward and slightly inward, extending arms until fully extended; hands meet (or nearly meet) in front of chest. Maintain stable body, no torso collapse or undue lean.\n* 4 s–5 s: Pause / lockout — arms fully extended, chest engaged, shoulders stable, slight squeeze of pecs/triceps at maximal contraction.\n* 5 s–7 s: Return phase — inhale, slowly bring handles back along same path, elbows bending, control maintained, cables under constant tension, until starting position is reached (handles near chest or slightly outward).\n* 7 s–8 s: Reset / end pose — subject briefly at rest in starting position (elbows bent, chest up, cables stable), then fade to black or hold final frame ~0.5 s before end.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Chest — especially the pectoralis major (sternal / mid-chest region)\n* Secondary: Anterior deltoids (front shoulders), triceps (for elbow extension), plus stabilizers like core, lower back, and sometimes hip/leg muscles (especially if standing).\nBenefits of Cable Chest Press\n* Provides constant tension through entire movement range — unlike free weights, cables maintain load across press + return phases, which can enhance muscle activation and growth.\n* Versatile: you can perform it standing or seated, adjust pulley height or handle spacing to slightly shift emphasis across upper/mid/lower chest or vary shoulder involvement.Safer / Joint-friendly alternative vs heavy bench-pressing: no heavy barbell overhead load, more controlled motion, easier to manage form and reduce risk.\nTips & Technique Notes\n* Keep torso stable — if standing, use a staggered stance or small step forward for balance. Avoid leaning excessively or arching back\n* Elbows should track naturally — don’t flare wildly; maintain a controlled, aligned path for arms during press.\n* Use a weight that lets you push smoothly — avoid jerky motion or bouncing; cables’ constant resistance requires good control for maximum muscle engagement.\n* For variation/targeting: adjust pulley height (slightly higher or lower than chest) or handle grip — can shift emphasis to upper chest, lower chest, or even more triceps/shoulder involvement depending on angle.",
