      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional fitness clip — ~8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920 × 1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Realistic gym tones — soft but clear lighting, neutral colors (machine: metal/black or grey, subject in neutral/solid gym wear), gentle highlight on arms/chest during motion\n* Sound: Soft gym ambient (machine pad sliding, quiet breathing, slight room echo), no voice-over (or optional subtle breathing cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Gym (or home-gym if you have the machine) — seat + backpad of the Pec-Deck machine, weights loaded, gym floor visible, background slightly blurred to keep focus on subject + machine\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle or side-slightly-front — to capture full upper body, machine, pads and hand/arm movement clearly. Framing should allow view of pad start position, arm arc, and final contraction together.\n* Subject: use reference image, Athletic adult male, seated on Pec-deck machine, feet flat on floor, back firmly against back-pad, torso upright; wearing simple gym clothes (tank or fitted tee + shorts/training pants), ready to start.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Setup — subject sits on machine, grips handles (or rests forearms against pads) with elbows bent (~90°), shoulders relaxed, chest up, back pressed to pad, feet flat for stability. Arms open wide (start position), tension on machine visible.\n* 1 s–2 s: Begin motion — subject exhales, initiates movement by pushing pads/handles together in a controlled arcing path toward the midline of chest, engaging chest muscles (pectorals). Elbows stay bent, forearms move inward.\n* 2 s–4 s: Contraction phase — pads/handles meet (or come close) in front of chest, chest slightly “compressed,” muscles under tension. Shoulders stable, back pressed against pad, core engaged, slight squeeze at peak.\n* 4 s–5 s: Pause / peak contract — hold the “closed” position for ~0.2–0.5 s to emphasize pec contraction and mind-muscle connection.\n* 5 s–7 s: Return phase — inhale, slowly reverse the movement, letting arms move outward to start position, feeling stretch in the chest. Controlled, smooth motion; avoid letting weights slam back or jerking.\n* 7 s–8 s: Finish pose — arms fully opened (or just before full lockout), back stable, chest tall, final brief hold (~0.3–0.5 s), then fade or cut.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary targets: Pectoralis major (main chest), Pectoralis minor.\n* Secondary/support: front shoulders (anterior deltoids), stabilizers — core, upper-back/shoulder-stabilizing muscles.\nBenefits & Use-Case\n* The Pec Deck provides controlled, guided motion with constant resistance and greatly reduces stability demands compared to free-weight flyes.\n* Allows for chest isolation: ideal for muscle-building (hypertrophy), focusing on pec contraction without heavy involvement of arms/shoulders.\n* Good for beginners or those rehabbing/avoiding joint stress — machine supports posture and minimizes risk of form breakdown.\nForm & Safety Tips\n* Adjust seat so that elbows / forearms are in line with chest/shoulder height. Back should stay pressed against pad, feet flat for support.\n* Keep a slight bend in elbows throughout; avoid locking them out or fully straightening to prevent joint strain.\n* Move in a controlled, smooth arc: no jerking, no momentum; focus on chest contraction on the way in, and controlled stretch on the way out.\n* Do not overstretch: return the arms to start before discomfort; maintain muscle tension.",
