      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional body-weight workout clip — ~8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Color & Lighting: Natural or soft-studio lighting — neutral floor or mat, minimal distractions, warm skin tones; a subtle highlight on chest/arms to emphasize form\n* Sound: Soft ambient (floor mat shift, subtle breath), no voice-over (or optional faint breath-in / breath-out cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Clean floor or gym mat, enough space around; a stable medicine ball placed at center front. Background should be simple to keep focus on subject + movement.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low) — full body from head to heels visible, so that you capture hands on ball, torso alignment, and push-up motion clearly.\n* Subject: use reference image, Athletic adult Male, wearing fitted workout clothes (e.g. sleeveless top + shorts), starting in push-up position with hands on the medicine ball.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Setup — subject in high-plank with hands gripping the medicine ball directly under shoulders, fingers on ball for grip/stability, body in straight line from head to heels, core & glutes engaged, feet roughly hip-width.\n* 1 s–2 s: Descend begins — inhale, bend elbows at about 45° relative to torso (not flaring wide), lower chest toward ball slowly while maintaining rigid body alignment, core tight.\n* 2 s–4 s: Bottom position — chest gently touches or approaches the ball, elbows bent, shoulders stabilizing, full control, maintain core and glute tension, avoid sagging hips.\n* 4 s–5 s: Brief pause — hold bottom position ~0.2–0.5 s to emphasize stretch/tension in chest and stabilizers.\n* 5 s–7 s: Press up — exhale, drive through hands on the ball, extend elbows, return to high-plank starting position, keeping body straight, core & glutes engaged.\n* 7 s–8 s: Lockout / finish pose — arms extended, torso stable, body aligned, hold briefly (~0.5 s), then fade out or cut.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Chest (pectoralis major), especially due to deeper push range; shoulders (deltoids), triceps.\n* Secondary / Stabilizers: Core (abs, obliques, lower back), shoulder stabilizers, forearms (for grip on ball), glutes & legs (to maintain full-body stability).\nBenefits & Purpose\n* Increased challenge over standard push-up: instability from medicine ball forces core and stabilizer muscles to engage more, improving balance and coordination.\n* Greater range of motion: chest lowers more deeply toward ball, potentially enhancing muscle stretch and activation.\n* Good upper-body strength & stability boost — useful if you want more than just standard push-up, and want to build functional strength, core stability, and shoulder/pec stability.\nForm & Safety Tips\n* Keep body rigid (like a plank) throughout — avoid sagging hips or arching back.\n* Keep elbows at ~45° to torso, not flared wide — reduces shoulder stress, improves pec/triceps activation.\n* Move slowly and controlled — don’t drop or bounce; smooth descent + ascent ensures stability and muscle control.\n* Beginners: If instability is too high or form breaks, start with regular push-ups until you have stable core & shoulder strength, then progress.",
