      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional workout clip — ~8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920 × 1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Real-gym or studio-gym lighting, neutral tones (dark/metal cable machine, simple flooring), warm skin tones; key light + subtle ambient fill to highlight subject and cable path\n* Sound: Soft gym ambient (cable / pulley hum, light weight-plate rattle if machine uses plates, subtle breath), no voiceover (or optional soft breathing cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Gym with cable-pulley machine (pulley high, cable attachment visible), clean space around machine, minimal clutter/background blur to emphasize subject + movement.\n* Camera: Medium-wide shot (¾-angle or slightly side/front) to capture full body — from head down to hips/legs — plus cable machine, attachment path, and arm movement. Allows clear view of starting position, arc of pullover, and finishing posture.\n* Subject: use reference image, Fit adult female, standing in front of cable machine, feet shoulder-width or staggered, knees slightly bent or in light semi-squat, torso angled ~ 30–45° forward from vertical, core tight, ready to pull. Clothing: gym attire (fitted top + shorts or training pants) to show muscle form.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Setup — hands grasp cable attachment (straight bar, rope, or handles) overhead or at high-pulley position; arms extended overhead, shoulders relaxed, torso leaned slightly forward (~30-45°), back straight, knees slightly bent, weight stable.\n* 1 s–2 s: Begin pullover — inhale, then with arms mostly straight (slight elbow bend for safety) start pulling the cable downward and back in wide arc, driving elbows toward hips, engaging lats/back.\n* 2 s–4 s: Mid-movement — cable passes through mid-arc; lats and back muscles stretching and activating; torso stable, core braced, slight hip bend & stable stance.\n* 4 s–5 s: Bottom / contracted position — arms roughly at hips or thighs, cable tension maintained, shoulders depressed (not shrugged), lat muscles engaged, chest slightly lifted, small squeeze at full contraction — hold ~0.2-0.5 s.\n* 5 s–7 s: Return phase — exhale, slowly allow cable to return arms overhead in controlled arc, feeling stretch in lats/back, arms extending without locking, maintain control of movement.\n* 7 s–8 s: Finish pose — arms overhead, torso stable, slight lean maintained, core tight, cable still taut, pause ~0.3-0.5 s before fade to black or repeat.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Latissimus dorsi (lats) — major back muscles; cable pullover strongly targets them.\n* Secondary: Chest (especially depending on arm path and posture), rear shoulders (deltoids), triceps (for elbow stability), plus stabilizers — core, lower back, hips/legs for balance.\nBenefits & Use-case\n* Keeps constant tension on lats and back throughout full range of motion — unlike free-weight pullovers where resistance changes due to gravity direction.\n* Safer and more joint-friendly than heavy free-weight overhead movements: less risk of uncontrolled arcs, easier to maintain form, better for shoulder mobility and back development.\n* Great as isolation/back accessory — useful if you lack weights or want to emphasize lats, widen upper back, and work on posture/stability.\nTips & Safety / Form Notes\n* Use a light to moderate weight initially — because of long lever (arms overhead) cable creates high torque; start light to master form.\n* Keep arms mostly straight (slight bend at elbows), avoid bending significantly — maintains lat stretch and reduces elbow/shoulder strain.\n* Torso posture: slightly bent forward at hips, neutral spine, core tight. Avoid excessive arching or rounding of back — helps protect spine.\n* Controlled tempo: both descent (pull) and return (lift) should be slow and smooth — don’t jerk or use momentum. Focus on mind-muscle connection, feeling lats contracting and stretching.\n* If possible: use attachments like straight bar, rope or wide handle depending on comfort — adjust grip width to what feels natural; wide grip tends to target lats more.",
      "character_prompt": "Subject: Adult female, athletic build, fitness attire. Relaxed standing A-pose, neutral expression.\nClothing: Athletic sportswear, workout gym clothes.\nStyle: Photo-realistic turnaround reference sheet, clean soft studio lighting.\nBackground: Clean, solid neutral gray studio background.",
      "muscles": "* Primary: Latissimus dorsi (lats) — major back muscles; cable pullover strongly targets them.\n* Secondary: Chest (especially depending on arm path and posture), rear shoulders (deltoids), triceps (for elbow stability), plus stabilizers — core, lower back, hips/legs for balance.",
      "benefits": "& Use-case\n* Keeps constant tension on lats and back throughout full range of motion — unlike free-weight pullovers where resistance changes due to gravity direction.\n* Safer and more joint-friendly than heavy free-weight overhead movements: less risk of uncontrolled arcs, easier to maintain form, better for shoulder mobility and back development.\n* Great as isolation/back accessory — useful if you lack weights or want to emphasize lats, widen upper back, and work on posture/stability.\nTips & Safety / Form Notes\n* Use a light to moderate weight initially — because of long lever (arms overhead) cable creates high torque; start light to master form.\n* Keep arms mostly straight (slight bend at elbows), avoid bending significantly — maintains lat stretch and reduces elbow/shoulder strain.\n* Torso posture: slightly bent forward at hips, neutral spine, core tight. Avoid excessive arching or rounding of back — helps protect spine.\n* Controlled tempo: both descent (pull) and return (lift) should be slow and smooth — don’t jerk or use momentum. Focus on mind-muscle connection, feeling lats contracting and stretching.\n* If possible: use attachments like straight bar, rope or wide handle depending on comfort — adjust grip width to what feels natural; wide grip tends to target lats more.",
