      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength-clip, ~8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Realistic gym- or home-gym tones — neutral floor/wall, weight plate metallic or dark, warm skin tones; soft key light + subtle ambient fill to highlight subject and weight plate.\n* Sound: Soft ambient gym sounds (slight plate clink, floor/foot shuffle, breath), no voice-over (or optional minimal breath cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Simple workout space — could be gym floor or home-gym, minimal clutter, good contrast between subject and background.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or eye-level) to capture full body from waist up, hands, plate and pressing motion.\n* Subject: use reference image, Fit adult male, athletic build, wearing fitted workout clothes (tank-top or tee + shorts/leggings), standing stable with feet shoulder-width, knees slightly bent, core engaged.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Setup — subject stands upright, holding a weight plate vertically against chest/upper abdomen with both hands — fingers around plate edges, elbows slightly bent, wrists neutral. Shoulders back & down, chest up, feet shoulder-width apart, core braced.\n* 1 s–2 s: Prepare — take a breath in, tighten abs & glutes, ensure stable base, focus forward.\n* 2 s–4 s: Press phase — exhale, push the plate straight forward (or slightly upward depending on form), arms extending until nearly straight (without locking elbows harshly), pressing out until arms are extended or plate reaches comfortable distance in front of chest. Keep wrists neutral, elbows slightly soft.\n* 4 s–5 s: Pause / contraction — hold the extended position ~0.2–0.5 s; chest, shoulders, triceps engaged, plate stable, posture strong.\n* 5 s–7 s: Return — inhale, slowly bring the plate back toward the chest, controlling the motion, elbows bending back, plate returning to start position against chest/upper abdomen.\n* 7 s–8 s: Reset / finish pose — plate close to chest, subject upright, core stable, slight squeeze of chest/triceps, hold ~0.3–0.5 s then fade or gently end.\nMuscles / Focus\nThe plate press primarily targets:\n* Chest (Pectoralis Major) — the main driver during the press.\n* Secondary muscles: front shoulders (Anterior Deltoid), triceps (Triceps Brachii) — for arm extension and stabilization.\n* Stabilizers and supporting muscles: core (abs, lower back), upper-back and scapular stabilizers, serratus (for shoulder/scapula control), plus some involvement from forearms and grip muscles due to holding plate.\nBenefits & Purpose\n* Minimal equipment — only a weight plate needed; great for home-gym or where dumbbells/barbells aren’t available.\n* Helps isolate chest, shoulders, triceps while also forcing core stability (since pressing the plate away from body challenges balance and posture).\n* Useful as a “finisher” or accessory movement in a push-day workout — good volume, controlled movement, lower joint stress compared to heavy presses.\nForm & Safety / Tips\n* Use a light-to-moderate weight plate — since the plate is pressed out away from your body, even modest weight creates torque and stability demand; start with lighter (10–15 lb / 5–7 kg) plates if new.\n* Keep back straight, core and glutes engaged throughout — avoid arching back or letting torso sway. Shoulders should stay down and back (not shrugged) to protect joints.\n* Use a controlled tempo — slow press out & return; avoid jerky motion or swinging the plate. Focus on chest contraction and proper alignment.\n* Keep wrists neutral and elbows slightly bent (avoid locking out hard) to reduce risk of wrist/elbow strain",
