      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength-clip, ~8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Neutral gym- or home-gym tones — matte floor or yoga-mat, metallic dumbbells, warm/neutral skin tones. Soft key light (from side/top) + gentle ambient fill to keep background minimally distracting.\n* Sound: Subtle ambient noise (soft floor mat contact, light dumbbell clinks, controlled breath), no voiceover (or optional very soft breathing cues).\nScene Setup\n* Location: Clean floor space (gym or home), preferably with a mat or padded surface; enough room to lie flat and extend arms. Background simple; focal depth slight blur to emphasize the subject and dumbbells.\n* Camera: Medium-wide shot, ¾-angle or side/ slightly low — capturing full body from head to knees/feet, dumbbells, and motion path. Allows clear view of torso alignment, arm movement, dumbbells, and floor contact.\n* Subject: use reference image, Fit adult male, athletic build, wearing fitted workout clothes (tank or t-shirt + shorts/leggings), lying flat on floor with knees bent (feet flat), dumbbells in hands, ready to press.\nAction / Beats (0 s – 8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Setup — subject lies flat on floor (mat), knees bent, feet flat; dumbbells in hands, arms extended upward over chest (or slightly wide), elbows straight but not locked, wrists neutral — starting position.\n* 1 s–2 s: Brace — subject draws breath, engages core and glutes, ensures shoulder blades & upper back contact floor, ready to press.\n* 2 s–4 s: Press — exhale, push dumbbells upward (or maintain press if starting from top), arms extending until near-lockout; dumbbells move straight without flaring elbows wide. Chest/triceps engage; shoulders stable.\n* 4 s–5 s: Pause / contraction — at full extension, hold briefly (~0.2–0.5 s), with pecs/triceps engaged, dumbbells stable overhead, body steady.\n* 5 s–7 s: Lower / reset — inhale, slowly lower dumbbells until upper arms (or elbows) touch floor (or near floor) — range limited by floor contact. Maintain control; don’t bounce — smooth descent.\n* 7 s–8 s: Finish / hold — dumbbells resting lightly on floor (or just above), subject breathing, body relaxed but stable, final hold ~0.3-0.5 s; fade out or end clip.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Chest (Pectoralis major — especially middle/sternal head), but emphasis shifts towards triceps due to limited bottom range (floor stops full stretch).\n* Secondary: Shoulders (anterior deltoids), stabilizers: core, upper-back (shoulder-blade stabilizers). Because motion is shorter and more controlled, there is less shoulder joint stress compared to full bench press.\nBenefits & Use-Case\n* Safer alternative to bench press or full-range dumbbell press — floor limits range of motion, reducing shoulder external-rotation and lowering risk of shoulder strain.\n* Great for building lockout strength and strengthening triceps (often the weak part of bench-press or pressing lifts).\n* Minimal equipment needed — just dumbbells + floor/mat. Useful for home workouts or when bench is unavailable.\n* Helps maintain pressing volume without overloading shoulders — good for recovery phases or those with shoulder stress.\nForm & Safety / Tips\n* Keep back & shoulder blades flat on floor — no excessive arch. Helps protect spine and ensures stable base.\n* Lower weights slowly and controlled — avoid bouncing or dropping dumbbells onto floor; don’t let elbows crash hard — smoothly touch floor, maintain tension.\n* Don’t flare elbows excessively — aim for ~45° elbow angle to avoid shoulder strain and maximize chest/triceps activation.\n* Use appropriate weight — since range of motion is limited, even moderate weights can be challenging; start with manageable dumbbells then progress gradually.",
