      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength-clip, ~8 seconds\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Realistic gym or simple home-gym tones — neutral/dark background or gym floor, metal or dark weight plates, warm skin tones; soft key light + ambient fill to highlight subject and plates.\n* Sound: Soft ambient (plate metal clink or subtle rub, soft breath), no voice-over (or optional minimal breath cue)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Clean workout space — could be a gym floor or home-gym, minimal clutter to keep focus on subject + plates.\n* Camera: Medium-wide angle (slightly low / ¾-angle) to show full upper body — from knees up, including arms & plates — to clearly show motion path and plate press.\n* Subject: use reference image, Fit adult female, athletic build, wearing gym clothes (fitted top + shorts/leggings), standing with feet shoulder-width or slightly apart, ready to perform Svend Press.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Setup — subject stands upright, holding two weight plates pressed together (“pinched”) in front of chest. Plates pressed between palms, fingers pointing forward, elbows bent slightly. Core engaged, chest up, shoulders back.\n* 1 s–2 s: Brace posture — tighten core, engage glutes and back, ensure stable stance.\n* 2 s–4 s: Press out — exhale, extend arms forward horizontally, pushing the plates away from chest. Maintain inward squeeze on plates throughout — emphasis on chest contraction. Arms extend until nearly straight (without locking elbows too harshly), plates pushed out in front of torso.\n* 4 s–5 s: Pause / contraction hold — hold the extended position ~0.2–0.5 s, feeling maximal pec contraction and inner-chest squeeze.\n* 5 s–7 s: Return — inhale, bring plates slowly and controlled back to chest, keeping tension on plates/pecs (don’t relax fully).\n* 7 s–8 s: Reset / finish frame — plates back at chest, body stable, chest up, small squeeze, hold ~0.3–0.5 s before fade or next rep.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Chest (mainly the pectorals, including the inner/sternal chest region)\n* Secondary: Shoulders (anterior deltoids), triceps (arm extension), core and stabilizers for posture & balance.\nWhy Use Svend Press — Benefits\n* High chest isolation with constant tension — the inward pinch + pressing out keeps pecs under continuous contraction, which helps with chest activation and hypertrophy.\n* Lower joint stress — uses light/moderate weight (plates), shorter lever-arm motion than heavy bench-press — easier on shoulders/rotator cuffs. Good as a warm-up, finisher, or for those with joint concerns.\n* Great for inner-chest and “pump” work, often overlooked by standard presses.\nTips & Notes\n* Use light-to-moderate plates (often 5 lb / 2–5 kg or 10 lb, depending on availability). Heavy plates make form hard and reduce control — which defeats the purpose of chest isolation.\n* Maintain a tight squeeze on the plates throughout — focus on pressing inward as well as outward, to maximize pec tension.\n* Keep core & posture engaged — avoid leaning or using momentum; control motion both out and back.\n* Can be used as warm-up, finisher, isolation set, or burnout — nice addition to a chest day without heavy load or risk.",
