      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional body-weight workout clip — ~8 seconds\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Neutral / natural — e.g. soft daylight or simple gym-light setup; floor mat or wood floor; subject in plain workout clothing to emphasize form\n* Sound: Soft ambient (floor-mat contact, soft breathing), no voice-over (or optional soft breath-in / breath-out cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Clean floor space (gym floor, mat, or home-gym) with enough room around to allow full push-up motion + slight weight shift. Background uncluttered, slight depth-of-field blur to keep focus on subject and movement.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle or side-slightly-low — capturing full body from head to heels, hands & shoulders, floor contact, so viewer clearly sees body alignment and shoulder-tap motion.\n* Subject: use reference image, Athletic adult male, wearing fitted workout attire (t-shirt/tank + shorts/leggings), in high-plank starting position (hands under shoulders, legs extended, body straight), ready to do push-up + shoulder taps.\nAction / Beats (0 s – 8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Setup — subject assumes high plank: hands slightly wider than shoulder-width, wrists under shoulders; body in a straight line head to heels; core and glutes engaged; legs maybe slightly wider for stability.\n* 1 s–2 s: Lower phase — begin controlled descent: elbows bending, body lowering toward floor, maintaining rigid plank shape (no sagging hips or piking), head/neck neutral.\n* 2 s–4 s: Push-up + press up — exhale, push through palms to extend arms and raise body back to plank-top. As you reach top, shift weight to one arm, lift the other hand and tap opposite shoulder lightly. Maintain stable hips/torso.\n* 4 s–5 s: Pause briefly after shoulder tap — body stable, core tight, shoulders square, grip ready.\n* 5 s–7 s: Repeat: lower into next push-up, then at top shift weight to other arm, tap opposite shoulder. Alternate taps each rep. Keep body alignment, avoid twisting hips.\n* 7 s–8 s: Finish in top-plank pose — arms extended, body straight, feet grounded, brief hold (~0.3–0.5 s), then fade to black or transition.\nMuscles / Focus (Primary & Stabilizers)\n* Primary: Chest (pectorals), shoulders (deltoids), triceps for the push-up component.\n* Stabilizers & Core: Abs, obliques, lower back — because shoulder-tap pushes require anti-rotation and core engagement to maintain a stable plank / body alignment while shifting weight.\n* Also recruits: Shoulders & stabilizer muscles (to stabilize one-arm load), glutes and legs (for maintaining straight body line)\nBenefits & Purpose\n* Combines upper-body strength (push-up) with core stability & balance — more functional and demanding than a regular push-up.\nHelps build anti-rotational core strength, shoulder stability, and better body control — useful for athleticism, posture, functional fitness.\n* Good calisthenics / bodyweight option — no equipment needed, can be done almost anywhere.\nForm & Technique Tips / Cautions\n* Keep spine neutral and body rigid — avoid hips sagging or rising; think “plank moving up and down.”\n* Elbows should track relatively close to ribs (not flared wide) when lowering — reduces shoulder strain, improves push-up effectiveness.\n* Do the shoulder tap only at the top after full arm extension (lock-out) — ensures stability and control before shifting weight.\n* Move slowly and controlled, especially the tap — avoid quick jerks or twisting hips, focus on balance and core engagement rather than speed or reps.\n* Beginners can widen feet for stability or perform a simpler floor-tap push-up variant until core/shoulder stability improves.",
