      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional body-weight workout clip — ~8 seconds\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Natural or soft gym-style light (e.g. daylight through window or neutral indoor lighting), simple floor or mat, workout clothes in neutral/dark tone, subtle warm-to-neutral palette.\n* Sound: Soft ambient (mat/ floor contact, breath sound), no voice-over (optionally soft breathing cue).\nScene Setup\n* Location: Clean floor space or gym, with a stable elevated surface (bench, box, step, sturdy chair etc.) — surface should be stable & non-slippery. Background minimal or slightly blurred so focus remains on subject and form.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low) so full body from head to heels is visible, hands on elevated surface and feet on floor — shows torso alignment and movement clearly.\n* Subject: use reference image, Fit adult male, wearing fitted workout clothes (tank/tee + shorts/leggings), ready in incline-push-up position.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Starting position — hands placed slightly wider than shoulder-width on elevated surface; feet on floor, body in a straight “plank” line from head to heels, core & glutes engaged, gaze slightly forward/ down to keep neck neutral.\n* 1 s–2 s: Brace core & glutes, ensure shoulders stacked over wrists, keep bodyline tight, prepare for descent.\n* 2 s–4 s: Descent — bend elbows slowly at ~45° relative to torso, lower chest toward elevated surface in a controlled motion, keeping torso straight (no sagging or bending at hips), inhale during descent.\n* 4 s–5 s: Bottom / pause — chest (or just above) nearly touches surface (or as much as comfortable), elbows bent, shoulders stable, bodyline maintained; brief hold (~0.2–0.5 s) to show tension/stretch in chest/triceps/core.\n* 5 s–7 s: Push up — exhale, press through palms to extend arms, push body back to starting plank-top, torso straight, core & glutes braced, shoulders stable.\n* 7 s–8 s: Lockout / finish pose — arms extended, torso straight, chest up, brief hold (~0.3–0.5 s), then fade to black or end clip.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Chest (pectoralis major and minor), especially lower/mid-chest relative to body angle.\n* Secondary: Triceps, anterior shoulders (deltoids), plus core, glutes and lower-body stabilizers (abs/back/hips) working to maintain straight bodyline and stability.\nWhy Use Incline Push-Up (Benefits)\n* Easier than standard push-up — supports less body weight due to elevated hands, making it a good progression for beginners or for practice toward full push-ups.\n* Still trains chest, shoulders, triceps — plus engages core and full-body stabilizers.\n* Versatile: can be done almost anywhere — bench, box, sofa edge, sturdy table — wherever safe stable elevation exists.\nForm & Safety Tips\n* Ensure body stays straight from head to heels — avoid dipping hips or arching back.\n* Use a stable, non-slip elevated surface — unstable platform may lead to wrist/shoulder injury or form break.\n* Keep hands slightly wider than shoulders, elbows tracking ~45° to torso — avoid flaring elbows too wide to protect shoulder joints.\n* Maintain core & glute engagement to stabilize body — don’t allow sagging or “hinging” at the hips.\n* Use a progressive approach — start with higher/easier incline surfaces and gradually lower height as strength improves.",
