      "id": "chest_low_cable_crossover_male",
      "name": "Low cable crossover",
      "gender": "male",
      "category": "chest",
      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional workout clip, ~8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Real-gym lighting (slightly moody but clear), neutral/matte gym floor, subtle warm-toned skin/light on subject, minimal background distraction — focus on subject + cables\n* Sound: Soft gym ambient (cable pulley tension hum, slight floor shuffle, controlled breathing), no voice-over (or optional soft breath-in / breath-out cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Cable-crossover / functional-trainer machine in a gym or home-gym. Both low-pulleys (bottom of machine) loaded equally, handles attached. Space cleared so subject stands between the two towers.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle from front (slightly low) — capturing subject from head to mid-thigh, showing cable machine pulleys, full arm movement path (start at sides/back, finish in front), torso alignment & feet stance.\n* Subject: use reference image, Athletic adult male, wearing fitted gym clothes (tank or snug t-shirt + shorts or training pants), ready to perform the exercise.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Setup — subject stands in the center between the two cable towers, each hand grabbing a handle with a neutral or slight under-hand/forward facing grip (palm orientation depending on preference), arms extended downward/away to sides/back, cables taut. Feet about shoulder-width, maybe staggered or one foot forward for stability, slight bend in knees, torso upright, shoulders back & down, core engaged.\n* 1 s–2 s: Pre-stretch / brace — subject loads chest: slight backward lean or just stable posture, arms out wide — feeling stretch in pecs and lats, preparing for the crossing motion.\n* 2 s–4 s: Pull / crossover — exhale, and smoothly draw both handles upward and inward in a wide arc (somewhat “hug-as-if-embracing-a-tree” motion), bringing hands together in front of the chest or slightly above abdomen. Elbows slightly bent (not locked), shoulders stable (not shrugged).\n* 4 s–5 s: Peak contraction / hold — hands meet in front, chest muscles squeezed (pecs), slightly squeeze/contract for ~0.2–0.5 s for maximum muscle engagement. Shoulders down, core and posture tight.\n* 5 s–7 s: Return / stretch — inhale, slowly reverse the path: let handles arc back and outwards to starting position, arms gradually widening, chest stretching, cables under constant tension, avoid letting handles snap back.\n* 7 s–8 s: Reset / ready for next rep — subject in starting wide-arms position, cables loaded, chest poised; slight pause (~0.3 s) before next rep or fade out.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Chest — especially upper/inner portion of Pectoralis major (clavicular/sternal fibers) and wider chest span.\n* Secondary: Front shoulders (anterior deltoids), stabilizers — muscles like Serratus anterior (for scapular control), upper-back stabilizers, plus core for posture and balance.\nBenefits / Why Use Low Cable Crossover\n* Provides constant tension through full range of motion — from stretch (arms back) to contraction (arms forward), which is excellent for hypertrophy / chest definition.\n* Targets chest from an angle that many pressing movements (bench-press, dips) don’t — especially good for upper & inner-chest development / shaping\n* Low impact on joints compared to heavy free-weight pressing; motion is controlled, shoulder stress reduced if form is correct.\nForm & Safety / Technique Tips\n* Use moderate/light weight — avoid heavy loads especially when learning, to maintain control and correct form (important because cables give constant tension along entire motion).\n* Keep a slight bend in elbows throughout — avoid locking arms straight or flaring elbows wide; this helps protect shoulder joints and ensures chest, not arms, carry the load.\n* Maintain shoulders down & back, chest up, core braced — avoid shrugging or collapsing torso. Stability comes from controlled posture, not momentum.\n* Move slow & controlled — especially on both inward (concentric) and outward (eccentric) phases; avoid swinging or letting cables “snap” back.\n* Stand in staggered or split-stance (one foot slightly ahead) for better balance/control — helps counteract pull and maintain posture.",
