      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength clip — ~8 seconds long.\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps.\n* Lighting & Color: Realistic gym/home-gym tones (bars or bench metal, neutral background, warm/neutral skin tones), soft key-light + ambient fill to highlight form and muscle lines.\n* Sound: Soft ambient (slight metal/bench creak if applicable, quiet breath, subtle floor/foot noise), no voice-over (or optional soft breath-cue).\nScene Setup\n* Location: Gym or home-gym dip station (parallel bars / dip bars) or a sturdy bench/chair if doing bench-dip/bench-style. Background uncluttered or softly blurred to keep focus on form and movement.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle or side-angle (slightly low) — capturing full upper body + arms + bars/bench, so you can view the dip motion clearly (down and up).\n* Subject: use reference image, Fit adult male wearing gym-appropriate attire (tank/tee + shorts or gym pants), gripping dip bars or bench edge, body weight supported on arms, ready to dip.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Setup — subject grips parallel bars (or bench edge), arms locked out, shoulders over wrists, body suspended (or feet extended if bench-dip), core engaged, posture stable.\n* 1 s–2 s: Stabilize upper body: shoulders pulled down & back, chest up, torso upright — prepare to descend.\n* 2 s–4 s: Descent — bend elbows slowly, lower body in controlled manner until elbows about 90° (or upper arms parallel to ground), keeping elbows tucked close to sides, shoulders stable.\n* 4 s–5 s: Bottom / pause — hold briefly (~0.2–0.5 s) at bottom to show stretch/tension on triceps (and chest if leaning forward slightly). Core & shoulder-blades remain stable.\n* 5 s–7 s: Push up — exhale, press through hands, extending elbows to raise body back up until arms lock out; maintain shoulder stability and avoid shrugging.\n* 7 s–8 s: Lock-out / finish pose — arms extended, body stable, slight squeeze at top (focus on triceps/shoulders/chest), brief hold (~0.3–0.5 s), then fade out or hold ready for next rep.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Triceps Brachii (back of the upper arm) — main driver of the pressing/extension motion.\n* Secondary / Supporting: Pectoralis Major / chest (especially if leaning slightly forward), shoulders (deltoids), forearms (for grip), and stabilizers including core and upper-back muscles for posture and control.\nBenefits & Use-Case\n* Great compound upper-body movement — builds triceps strength, also engages chest, shoulders, and upper-body stabilizers.\n* Versatile: can be done on parallel bars (full bodyweight), bench/chair (bodyweight + easier), or elevated surfaces — good for home or gym.\n* Helps improve pressing strength, elbow-extension control, upper-arm definition and functional push strength (useful for everyday pushing motions).\nForm / Safety & Technique Tips\n* Keep shoulders down and back (no shrugging) and maintain good posture throughout — prevents shoulder strain.\n* Keep elbows tucked close to sides (don’t flare wide) — ensures triceps activation and reduces shoulder stress.\n* Lower slowly — avoid dropping quickly; maintain control of descent and ascent to protect joints and maximize muscle work.\n* If full-bar dips are too hard: start with bench/chair dips to build strength; or adjust foot positioning to reduce load.\n* Warm up shoulders properly — dips demand shoulder mobility; if shoulders are tight/weak, risk of strain goes up.",
