      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength-clip — ~8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Real-gym or home-gym tones — bench grey/black, dumbbells metallic, warm/neutral skin tones. Soft key light (from above/side) + mild ambient fill to highlight subject and dumbbells.\n* Sound: Soft gym ambient (dumbbell clinks, bench creak, subtle breath), no voice-over (optionally soft breath-in / breath-out cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Gym or home-gym with an adjustable decline bench; bench set at ~30° decline; space clean and uncluttered; background slightly blurred for focus on the subject & dumbbells.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle, slightly low — capturing the full body from head to mid-thigh, bench angle, arms + dumbbells — so you can clearly see the arc of the fly, bench position, and torso alignment.\n* Subject: use reference image, Fit adult male, athletic build, wearing fitted gym clothes (tank or tee + shorts or gym pants), lying back on the decline bench, feet secured/placed for stability, ready with dumbbells in hands.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Setup — subject lies on decline bench, back/head supported, feet stable (on floor or foot holders), dumbbells held above chest, palms facing each other (neutral grip), elbows slightly bent (soft, not locked).\n* 1 s–2 s: Brace — retract and pinch shoulder blades, tighten core & glutes, create full-body tension; ensure dumbbells stable above chest, gaze neutral or forward-down.\n* 2 s–4 s: Descent / Fly down — inhale, and slowly lower dumbbells in a wide arc out to the sides; arms move mainly at the shoulder joint, keeping a constant slight bend in elbows; dumbbells move outward and down in a controlled arc until arms (or upper arms) roughly reach parallel to floor (or until you feel a good stretch in lower-pec).\n* 4 s–5 s: Bottom / stretch pause — dumbbells out wide, chest stretched, shoulders stable, core & glutes tight; hold this bottom stretch ~0.2–0.5 s to emphasize muscle stretch and control.\n* 5 s–7 s: Concentric / Fly up — exhale, bring dumbbells back up in same arc, squeezing chest (especially lower chest / sternal pec) as arms come together; avoid banging weights — bring them close but control motion, keeping tension on pecs.\n* 7 s–8 s: Top / hold — dumbbells nearly meeting or just apart above chest, arms extended (but elbows still soft), chest contracted, shoulder blades stable, body tight; hold for ~0.3–0.5 s, then (optionally) fade out or prep for next rep.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Lower chest (sternal head of Pectoralis Major) — decline angle maximizes activation of lower-pec fibers.\n* Secondary: Shoulders (anterior deltoids), stabilizers (shoulder-girdle, scapular stabilizers), possibly triceps for elbow stability; core and glutes help maintain body stability on decline bench.\nBenefits & Use-Case\n* Targets lower chest more effectively than flat or incline flyes — helps build size and definition especially in lower pec region.\n* Provides a deep stretch + controlled contraction which improves chest flexibility, increases range of motion, and may help with posture & shoulder mobility.\n* Good as an isolation / finishing exercise after heavier compound lifts (presses), to fully fatigue and pump the chest muscles.\nTips & Safety / Technique Notes\n* Use light to moderate dumbbell weight — decline flyes put significant stress on shoulder joint due to arm-lever length; heavy weight may lead to shoulder issues.\n* Keep elbows slightly bent throughout — avoid locking or fully straightening; prevents elbow/shoulder joint strain.\n* Don’t lower dumbbells beyond comfortable stretch/shoulder flexibility — forcing too deep may risk shoulder strain or injury.\n* Maintain full-body tightness — shoulder blades retracted/pinched, core and glutes engaged, feet stable (especially on decline bench) to avoid sliding or lower-back stress.\n* Use controlled tempo — slow descent and controlled lift, avoid bouncing or dropping dumbbells, to maximize muscle tension and safety.",
