      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional body-weight clip — ~8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Everyday home-gym or living-room lighting (soft natural or overhead), neutral background, warm skin tones; keep environment simple and distraction-free\n* Sound: Soft ambient (floor/bench creak, subtle breathing), no voice-over (or optional soft breath cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: A sturdy bench, chair, or couch seat in a clean, uncluttered space — stable and non-slip floor, enough room in front for legs to extend.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly side / slightly low) so whole upper body + arms + support (bench/ chair) + leg position visible. This shows dip motion clearly (down + up).\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, athletic or beginner-friendly build, wearing comfortable workout clothes; seated on edge of bench/chair, ready to dip.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Setup — subject sits on edge of bench/chair, hands placed next to hips on the edge ( fingers facing forward), feet on floor, knees bent or legs extended (depending on difficulty). Body upright, shoulders back and down, chest up.\n* 1 s–2 s: Lift off — using arms, lift hips off seat so weight supported by hands, legs and hands. Keep arms straight, shoulders stable, core and glutes engaged.\n* 2 s–4 s: Descent — slowly bend elbows, lower body by sliding hips downward until elbows reach ~ 90°, upper arms parallel (or near) to floor. Keep elbows tucked next to sides, shoulders pressed down and back (not shrugged), avoid letting elbows flare wide.\n* 4 s–5 s: Bottom / pause — hold lowest position ~0.2–0.5 s, feel triceps under stretch and tension. Maintain core tightness, shoulders controlled, body upright.\n* 5 s–7 s: Press up — exhale, press through palms, extend elbows, lifting body back up until arms nearly straight, hips return to start position. Keep motion controlled, don’t lock elbows harshly or bounce.\n* 7 s–8 s: Finish pose — arms extended, body stable, brief hold ~0.3–0.5 s, then (optionally) sit back or end clip.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Triceps Brachii (main driver of elbow-extension during dips)\n* Secondary: Pectoralis Major (especially lower portion / chest side when leaning slightly), anterior deltoids (front shoulders), supporting stabilizers (shoulder-blade stabilizers, forearms for grip).\nBenefits & Why It’s Good for Beginners / Home\n* It’s a bodyweight exercise requiring minimal equipment (just a bench/chair), making it ideal for home workouts.\n* Targets triceps, while also engaging some chest and shoulders — useful as part of any upper-body routine.\n* Can be easily scaled: keep knees bent and feet closer to make light; extend legs for more load — so good for both beginners and intermediate users.\nForm & Safety / Common Mistakes to Avoid\n* Keep shoulders down + back — don’t let them collapse/roll forward during dips. Good shoulder positioning protects joints.\n* Keep elbows close to sides, not flared out — flared elbows shift load away from triceps and increase shoulder stress.\n* Don’t lower too deep — go until elbows ~ 90°, or as far as comfortable; going too low may stress shoulders.\n* Controlled motion — avoid bouncing or using momentum; descent and ascent should be deliberate to maximize muscle activation and reduce joint stress.",
      "character_prompt": "Subject: Adult male, athletic build, fitness attire. Relaxed standing A-pose, neutral expression.\nClothing: Athletic sportswear, workout gym clothes.\nStyle: Photo-realistic turnaround reference sheet, clean soft studio lighting.\nBackground: Clean, solid neutral gray studio background.",
      "muscles": "* Primary: Triceps Brachii (main driver of elbow-extension during dips)\n* Secondary: Pectoralis Major (especially lower portion / chest side when leaning slightly), anterior deltoids (front shoulders), supporting stabilizers (shoulder-blade stabilizers, forearms for grip).",
