      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength clip, ~8 seconds long\n* 1920 × 1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: gym-style lighting (neutral/metal bench/bar, slightly cool ambient, warm skin-tones), gentle key-light + subtle ambient fill so subject and bar are clear\n* Sound: soft gym ambient (plate clink, subtle breath), no voice-over (or optional soft breath cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: upright bench and barbell rack in gym; bench set upright (for seated press) or standing rack; background minimal, slight depth-of-field blur to focus on lifter + bar.\n* Camera: medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low) capturing full upper body, bar path, bench/rack — so view shows lifter, neck-bar position, arm path, and stability.\n* Subject: use reference image, Athletic adult male, wearing gym-appropriate clothes, seated upright (if seated version) or standing, gripping bar with overhand grip, ready to press.\nAction / Beats (0–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Setup — lifter sits (or stands) with barbell at shoulder-height / just behind neck, hands slightly wider than shoulder-width, palms forward, elbows under bar, core braced, back straight, eyes forward or slightly down.\n* 1 s–2 s: Brace & stabilize — shoulder blades slightly retracted/depressed, mid-back tight, feet flat (if seated) or planted (if standing), neck neutral (head slightly forward to avoid bar hitting).\n* 2 s–4 s: Press up — exhale, push bar upward overhead in vertical line, extending arms fully but without over-arching back; keep bar path vertical over head; torso stable.\n* 4 s–5 s: Lockout / hold top — arms extended, bar overhead (slightly behind head), shoulders stable, core engaged, brief hold ~0.2–0.5 s.\n* 5 s–7 s: Lower down — inhale, slowly lower bar behind neck back to shoulders/traps, control movement; avoid dropping too fast or letting bar crash.\n* 7 s–8 s: Reset pose — bar rests just behind neck/traps, grip stable, back/braces engaged, ready for next rep or fade out.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary target: should- ers — deltoids (front, side, rear), especially side/rear delts when arms travel behind head.\n* Secondary: upper-back (trapezius), triceps, serratus anterior, core (for stability), and stabilizers (rotator-cuff / shoulder-girdle).\nImportant: Risks & When to Avoid\n* The behind-the-neck press puts considerable strain on shoulder joints and rotator-cuffs; many trainers consider it risky, especially for those with limited shoulder mobility.\n* If your shoulder mobility or thoracic spine mobility is limited (or you have prior shoulder/neck issues), this exercise may cause discomfort or injury.\n* Bar path behind neck brings bar close to head/neck — poor form or loss of control can lead to unsafe bar contact with neck/back of head.\n* Many trainers recommend safer alternatives (front-bar overhead press, dumbbell shoulder press, neutral-grip press) to achieve shoulder development with less risk.",
