      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength-clip, ~8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Real-gym lighting — neutral gym tones (machine metal, bench padding), warm skin tones of subject, mild key-light from side or above + ambient fill to highlight form and handle movement.\n* Sound: Soft gym ambient (slight machine click/clank, controlled breathing), no voice-over (or optional faint breath cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Gym or home-gym with a chest-press / machine-bench press machine. The machine must have seat + back support + handles/press arms. Space neat/clean, background slightly blurred to keep attention on lifter & machine.\n* Camera: Medium-wide 3/4 angle (slightly low or eye-level) capturing upper-body, machine handles, full arm extension path, and seat/back so posture and movement path are clear.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, athletic or average build, in gym clothes (fitted tee or tank + shorts / gym pants), seated on machine bench — back and head resting on pad, feet on floor, ready to press.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Setup — subject sits upright, back & head firmly against seat pad, feet flat on floor (about shoulder-width). Adjust seat so handles are approximately at chest/pectoral level. Grip handles with full grip, wrists neutral, elbows bent slightly. Shoulders retracted / pressed into pad.\n* 1 s–2 s: Brace & ready — take a brief breath in, engage core & back, ensure stable posture (back flat, shoulders down/back), prepare to press.\n* 2 s–4 s: Press / concentric phase — exhale, push the handles forward until arms are (nearly) extended. Do not lock out elbows harshly. Press should be controlled and steady.\n* 4 s–5 s: Lockout / squeeze — at full extension, hold for ~0.2–0.5 s, focusing on chest contraction, keeping shoulder blades pressed into pad, maintaining control & stable posture.\n* 5 s–7 s: Return / eccentric phase — inhale, slowly bring handles back to start position under controlled tempo; resist momentum, feel pecs stretch slightly as arms retract.\n* 7 s–8 s: Reset / finish pose — handles near starting position, subject stable, back against pad, ready for next rep or end clip.\nMuscles / Benefits / Why Use Machine Bench Press\n* Primary Muscles Worked: Chest — pectoralis major (overall) and depending on seat/angle, portions of chest.\n* Secondary / Supporting Muscles: Triceps (for elbow extension), front shoulders (anterior deltoids), some activation in stabilizers but less than free-weight bench press.\n* Safer & Beginner-Friendly: Since machine enforces a fixed pressing path and provides back/seat support, it's easier to learn and reduces the risk of bad form or instability. Good when starting out or if bench-press form/spotter not available.\n* Less Need for Stabilizer Muscles: Because machine stabilizes the motion path, you can focus more on chest activation — useful for hypertrophy or isolation chest work without worrying about balance or bar control.\n* Convenient & Controlled: Easier to perform, adjust loads quickly, and often allows safe pushing to failure without spotter — convenient for gym circuits or saving time.\n* Good for Rehab / Joint Safety: The guided motion can be gentler on shoulders/ joints compared to free-weight bench press, beneficial if you are recovering or have mobility issues.\nTips / Form & Safety Recommendations\n* Adjust seat so that handles align at chest height — misaligned seat might strain shoulders or reduce effectiveness.\n* Keep back, shoulders and head pressed against seat pad throughout — avoid arching or lifting torso.\n* Use moderate weight — because stability is provided by machine, you can focus on controlled motion and muscle contraction. Avoid jerky presses or locking elbows harshly.\n* Lower handles with control (don’t bounce) to get full eccentric stretch; press smoothly for full range of motion for better chest engagement.\n* Use it as part of a larger chest routine — good as a “finish” or isolation set after heavier free-weight work.",
